.SH "BUGS"
.IX Header "BUGS"
.SS "Commands must be ordered"
.IX Subsection "Commands must be ordered"
The application does not check the sanity of the command line
arguments. For example running commands in wrong order. It makes no
sense trying to make a binary \fIpackage\fR before the package has been
built or installed.
.PP
.Vb 1
\&   cygbuild \-r 1 package conf make install
.Ve
.PP
The commands are always executed in listed order.
.SS "Other archive formats like *.zip are not recognized"
.IX Subsection "Other archive formats like *.zip are not recognized"
This porting tool only handles \f(CW\*(C`*.tar.gz\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`*.tar.bz2\*(C'\fR,
\&\f(CW\*(C`*.tar.lzma\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`*.tar.xz\*(C'\fR archives. To port e.g. a \f(CW\*(C`*.zip\*(C'\fR
archive, you need to manually convert it to a recognized format:
.PP
.Vb 6
\&    unzip package\-N.N.zip
\&    ... convert source archive to *.tar.gz
\&    tar \-cvf package\-1.1.tar.gz package\-N.N/
\&    ... Now proceed normally
\&    cd package\-N.N/
\&    cygbuild \-r 1 mkdirs files conf make install
.Ve
.SS "Reporting bugs"
.IX Subsection "Reporting bugs"
If you run into a bug, activate debug mode and send complete output
listing to the maintainer. Provide also an \s-1URL\s0 link to the source
package that you tried to build.
.PP
.Vb 3
\&    echo http://example.com/source      >  ~/tmp/error.log
\&    pwd; ls \-la . ..                    >> ~/tmp/error.log
\&    bash \-x cygbuild [options] CMD ...  >> ~/tmp/error.log 2>&1
.Ve
.SS "Slow program startup"
.IX Subsection "Slow program startup"
You may notice that the startup is a little slow. This is due to way
the program determining what many global variables need to be
available at runtime. The method of checking environment is not
particularly efficient (due to bash-scripting limitations in general).
E.g. same checks of version and release numbers are called multiple
times.
.SH "MISCELLANEOUS"
.IX Header "MISCELLANEOUS"
.SS "Makefiles and compiling libraries"
.IX Subsection "Makefiles and compiling libraries"
To compile libraries for Cygwin, the \f(CW\*(C`LDFLAGS\*(C'\fR should include option
\&\f(CW\*(C`\-no\-undefined\*(C'\fR. If there is \f(CW\*(C`Makefile(.in|.am)\*(C'\fR, after patching
them manually, you can regenerate the Makefiles with
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    autoreconf \-\-install \-\-force \-\-verbose
.Ve
.SS "yacc or lex file compiling notes"
.IX Subsection "yacc or lex file compiling notes"
Sometimes the \f(CW\*(C`*.y\*(C'\fR file won't compile. See thread \*(L"ftpcmd.y \*(--
syntax error\*(R" at
<http://lists.gnu.org/archive/html/help\-bison/2004\-04/msg00015.html>.
.PP
.Vb 2
\&    bison \-y ftpcmd.y
\&    ftpcmd.y:185.17: syntax error, unexpected "="
\&
\&    ...There are occurrences of "<tab>=<tab>{" in ftpcmd.y (in the
\&    wu\-ftpd 2.6.2 source release). Changing all of these to "<tab>{"
\&    fixes the problem \-\- and doesn\*(Aqt cause problems for Berkeley yacc,
\&    or for earlier versions of bison.
.Ve
.SS "Cygwin postinstall script conventions"
.IX Subsection "Cygwin postinstall script conventions"
If program X's \f(CW\*(C`postinstall\*(C'\fR is doing a \f(CW\*(C`cp\*(C'\fR, it does not preserve the \s-1ACL\s0
permissions. The \f(CW\*(C`postinstall\*(C'\fR script must be accompanied with \f(CWtouch(1)\fR
to create the new file before copying unto it or a call to \f(CW\*(C`chmod\*(C'\fR to set
reasonable permissions after the copying. If that's not done, the user may
end up having unreadable files. \s-1NOTE:\s0 \f(CW\*(C`cp \-p\*(C'\fR will not work, but \f(CW\*(C`install
\&\-m\*(C'\fR would.
(Cf. <http://cygwin.com/ml/cygwin\-apps/2005\-01/msg00148.html>).
.SS "Use of hard links"
.IX Subsection "Use of hard links"
Some ported packages may rely on hard links. Those are efficient only
under \s-1NTFS\s0 and not \s-1FAT\s0. Please include note to <package>.README that
the utility may not be best under \s-1FAT\s0 file systems.
.SS "setup.hint should list all dependencies"
.IX Subsection "setup.hint should list all dependencies"
The \fIrequires:\fR line is not only an indication of what to pull in,
but also what the package actually uses. These dependences are also
used to find the order of postinstall scripts (so, if package has any
postinstall scripts with \f(CW\*(C`#!/bin/sh\*(C'\fR, the scripts may not work
because the bash postinstall script was not run). So include all
direct dependences in the \fIrequires:\fR line, even if they are in
\&\fBBase\fR category.
(Cf. <http://cygwin.com/ml/cygwin\-apps/2008\-03/msg00070.html>).
